ce:section.ce:para:
The SEM photomicrograph (Fig. 1
a) of Al–5Ti–0.8C master alloy shows the presence of fine particles of 0.5–1μm size along with plate like particles in the Al matrix. The EDX microanalysis suggests that the fine particles are TiC, while the plate like particles are TiAl3. In the case of Al–5Ti–1.2C no TiAl3 particles could be detected (Fig. 1b). A thorough microstructural study showed that the number of TiC particles is less in Al–5Ti–0.8C master alloy when compared to Al–5Ti–1.2C. At higher magnification (Fig. 1c and d) the photomicrographs show the morphology of TiC particles, which are mostly faceted and blocky in nature. The EDX spectrum obtained from the fine particles (Fig. 1e) shows the presence of Al, Ti and C peaks. The Al peak observed in the spectrum is possibly the contribution of the matrix Al due to the fineness of the TiC particles. The XRD pattern (Fig. 2
) of the bulk and extracted particles confirms the presence of fcc TiC in the master alloys. The absence of TiAl3 peaks in the extracted particles of Al–5Ti–1.2C master alloy confirms the result of microscopy. The composition of the alloys has been confirmed from both wet chemical analysis and also from the weight fraction of the extracted TiC particles in the master alloys. The existence of TiAl3 particles in the Al–5Ti–0.8C can be understood from the fact that the ratio of the weight fraction of Ti and C in TiC is 4:1 and hence 0.8% C needs about 3.2% Ti to form TiC. The excess Ti available in the master alloy reacts with Al and forms TiAl3. In case of Al–5Ti–1.2C, the Ti:C ratio is very close to 4:1 and hence no excess Ti is available for the formation of TiAl3. Thus, the present study could successfully suppress the formation of TiAl3 and could demonstrate the formation of single phase TiC in Al matrix in Al–5Ti–1.2C master alloy.
